00:27:21.120 --> 00:27:23.440
By remembering one detail,
you've narrowed it down

00:27:23.440 --> 00:27:25.694
from 25,000 to 3.

00:27:25.694 --> 00:27:27.860
Imagine how that can work
in your professional life,

00:27:27.860 --> 00:27:31.050
if you remember one small detail
about one client, about one

00:27:31.050 --> 00:27:34.490
transaction, about one problem,
one patient, one crime scene.

00:27:34.490 --> 00:27:38.660
And if you ever wondered about
the power of facial expression,

00:27:38.660 --> 00:27:42.295
nonverbal communication, eye
contact, and body language,

00:27:42.295 --> 00:27:44.230
did you ever see this picture?

00:27:44.230 --> 00:27:44.957
Sure you have.

00:27:44.957 --> 00:27:47.040
And if I asked you for
your visual analysis of it,

00:27:47.040 --> 00:27:48.581
I don't want to hear
Osama bin Laden.

00:27:48.581 --> 00:27:49.970
Because he's not in the picture.

00:27:49.970 --> 00:27:53.440
It's 12 to 14 people looking
fraught and anxious and

00:27:53.440 --> 00:27:54.184
nervous.

00:27:54.184 --> 00:27:56.100
And they're looking at
something we can't see.

00:27:56.100 --> 00:27:57.670
Intellectually, we may know
what they're looking at.

00:27:57.670 --> 00:27:59.150
But we don't know what
they're looking at.

00:27:59.150 --> 00:28:00.900
We can't see what
they're looking at.

00:28:00.900 --> 00:28:02.300
And to show you different
perspectives, when

00:28:02.300 --> 00:28:04.591
I train officers who are
about to deploy to Afghanistan

00:28:04.591 --> 00:28:06.417
and I say, what do you
see in this picture?

00:28:06.417 --> 00:28:08.500
They'll say, you know, the
only guy doing any work

00:28:08.500 --> 00:28:11.040
in that picture is in uniform.

00:28:11.040 --> 00:28:12.350
Because that's what they see.

00:28:12.350 --> 00:28:14.077
That's where their eyes go.

00:28:14.077 --> 00:28:16.410
Now, I'm going to ask you to
compare and contrast these.

00:28:16.410 --> 00:28:18.370
And please don't say what
my NYPD officers say,

00:28:18.370 --> 00:28:20.360
every time without exception,
don't say before marriage

00:28:20.360 --> 00:28:21.060
and after.

00:28:21.060 --> 00:28:24.940
That's not the comparison
I'm looking for.

00:28:24.940 --> 00:28:27.060
It's not what I'm looking for.

00:28:27.060 --> 00:28:31.654
How are these pictures similar
or different in any way?

00:28:31.654 --> 00:28:33.990
AUDIENCE: The upper
figure has her hands out.

00:28:33.990 --> 00:28:37.747
And the bottom figure
has her hand underneath--

00:28:37.747 --> 00:28:39.330
AMY E. HERMAN: Under
her right breast.

00:28:39.330 --> 00:28:40.110
AUDIENCE: Yes,
that is what it is.

00:28:40.110 --> 00:28:41.360
AMY E. HERMAN: Yes, that's it.

00:28:41.360 --> 00:28:42.357
I'll say anything.

00:28:42.357 --> 00:28:44.940
So the woman in the top picture
has her hands behind her head.

00:28:44.940 --> 00:28:46.398
And the woman in
the bottom picture

00:28:46.398 --> 00:28:48.560
has one hand on the couch
and one hand cupping

00:28:48.560 --> 00:28:49.340
her right breast.

00:28:49.340 --> 00:28:52.060
Although in my detective class
in the NYPD, a couple weeks

00:28:52.060 --> 00:28:54.480
ago, someone said-- this is
why I wrote a book, because I

00:28:54.480 --> 00:28:56.063
couldn't make this
stuff up-- he said,

00:28:56.063 --> 00:28:59.080
how do you know someone's
not trapped under there?

00:28:59.080 --> 00:29:01.240
And I thought, I would
have never thought

00:29:01.240 --> 00:29:04.020
of that in a million years.

00:29:04.020 --> 00:29:05.770
This is why I write a
book, because people

00:29:05.770 --> 00:29:07.170
say incredible things.

00:29:07.170 --> 00:29:07.670
What else?

00:29:07.670 --> 00:29:08.800
Similarities and differences?

00:29:08.800 --> 00:29:09.210
Yes?

00:29:09.210 --> 00:29:10.550
AUDIENCE: One has the
eyes open, eyes closed.

00:29:10.550 --> 00:29:12.780
AMY E. HERMAN: Yes, women in
top picture has her eyes open.

00:29:12.780 --> 00:29:14.270
The woman in the bottom
picture has her eyes closed.

00:29:14.270 --> 00:29:15.000
What else?

00:29:15.000 --> 00:29:16.910
AUDIENCE: There's no
background drapery.

00:29:16.910 --> 00:29:19.620
AMY E. HERMAN: Yes, no
background and drapery.

00:29:19.620 --> 00:29:20.416
Yes, what else?

00:29:20.416 --> 00:29:22.290
AUDIENCE: They're leaning
on different sides.

00:29:22.290 --> 00:29:23.831
AMY E. HERMAN: Yes,
they're reclining

00:29:23.831 --> 00:29:24.940
in different directions.

00:29:24.940 --> 00:29:27.000
What else?

00:29:27.000 --> 00:29:27.642
Yes?

00:29:27.642 --> 00:29:29.100
AUDIENCE: They're
both naked women.

00:29:29.100 --> 00:29:31.230
AMY E. HERMAN: They're
both naked white women

00:29:31.230 --> 00:29:32.350
who are brunettes.

00:29:32.350 --> 00:29:33.519
What else?

00:29:33.519 --> 00:29:35.060
AUDIENCE: One is
slim and one is not.

00:29:35.060 --> 00:29:36.101
AMY E. HERMAN: Thank you.

00:29:36.101 --> 00:29:37.820
He just said, one is
slim and one is not.

00:29:37.820 --> 00:29:39.770
That's all we have to say.

00:29:39.770 --> 00:29:41.770
But that's not even the
reason I juxtaposed them

00:29:41.770 --> 00:29:42.787
for your comparison.

00:29:42.787 --> 00:29:44.870
I was going to stand here
until somebody mentioned

00:29:44.870 --> 00:29:46.578
the difference in
their girth, because it

00:29:46.578 --> 00:29:48.625
is a sizable difference.

00:29:48.625 --> 00:29:50.250
Eight years ago I
put these pictures up

00:29:50.250 --> 00:29:52.020
at a psychiatric conference.

00:29:52.020 --> 00:29:54.039
And a very senior
psychiatrist stood up.

00:29:54.039 --> 00:29:55.830
And he said, with the
most beautiful accent

00:29:55.830 --> 00:29:57.660
I've ever heard-- he
gave me permission

00:29:57.660 --> 00:30:00.076
not only to repeat his comments,
but to imitate his accent

00:30:00.076 --> 00:30:01.440
because I did a good job of it.

00:30:01.440 --> 00:30:03.690
He said, (WITH ACCENT) the
woman in the bottom picture

00:30:03.690 --> 00:30:04.772
is morbidly obese.

00:30:04.772 --> 00:30:06.980
He was from South Africa
beautiful, beautiful accent.

00:30:06.980 --> 00:30:08.360
He said, (WITH ACCENT) The
woman in the bottom picture's

00:30:08.360 --> 00:30:09.300
morbidly obese.

00:30:09.300 --> 00:30:11.341
The woman in the top
picture's perfectly healthy.

00:30:11.341 --> 00:30:13.860
And I said, you know doctor,
with all due respect,

00:30:13.860 --> 00:30:15.985
can you really tell me the
woman in the top picture

00:30:15.985 --> 00:30:17.240
is perfectly healthy?

00:30:17.240 --> 00:30:19.460
I said, how do you know
she's not schizophrenic?

00:30:19.460 --> 00:30:21.543
How do you know she doesn't
have a blood disorder?

00:30:21.543 --> 00:30:23.050
How do you know she's not deaf?

00:30:23.050 --> 00:30:24.297
And he said, oh I'm so sorry.

00:30:24.297 --> 00:30:25.630
I can't believe how wrong I was.

00:30:25.630 --> 00:30:26.546
I said, you know what?

00:30:26.546 --> 00:30:27.300
You weren't wrong.

00:30:27.300 --> 00:30:30.210
Your choice of words was poor.

00:30:30.210 --> 00:30:31.910
And this is my
opportunity to tell

00:30:31.910 --> 00:30:34.010
my sessions there are
very, very few things that

00:30:34.010 --> 00:30:36.050
are 100% in your control.

00:30:36.050 --> 00:30:38.500
Choice of words is one of them.

00:30:38.500 --> 00:30:42.060
Both in speaking and in writing,
choice of words is up to you.

00:30:42.060 --> 00:30:45.170
And I implore my classes,
don't make poor word choices.

00:30:45.170 --> 00:30:47.370
I hear people do
it all the time.

00:30:47.370 --> 00:30:50.430
I want you to tell me what you
see here, not what you think.

00:30:50.430 --> 00:30:52.960
What do you see in this picture?

00:30:52.960 --> 00:30:53.732
Yes?

00:30:53.732 --> 00:30:56.197
AUDIENCE: It's a photograph
of a middle-aged looking--

00:30:56.197 --> 00:30:58.530
AMY E. HERMAN: Ah, I'm very
sensitive to the term middle

00:30:58.530 --> 00:30:59.030
age.

00:30:59.030 --> 00:31:01.869
Give me a ballpark here.

00:31:01.869 --> 00:31:02.910
AUDIENCE: Oh, of her age?

00:31:02.910 --> 00:31:03.814
AMY E. HERMAN: Yeah.

00:31:03.814 --> 00:31:04.941
AUDIENCE: Over 30?

00:31:04.941 --> 00:31:05.690
AMY E. HERMAN: OK.

00:31:05.690 --> 00:31:06.301
Fair enough.

00:31:06.301 --> 00:31:06.800
Fair enough.

00:31:06.800 --> 00:31:08.630
Because middle aged
to me is 35 to 70.

00:31:08.630 --> 00:31:10.380
So over 30 is good.

00:31:10.380 --> 00:31:14.200
So you see a picture of two
people, a woman who's over 30

00:31:14.200 --> 00:31:14.907
and what else?

00:31:14.907 --> 00:31:17.089
AUDIENCE: I see a
boy, a small one.

00:31:17.089 --> 00:31:17.922
AMY E. HERMAN: Good.

00:31:17.922 --> 00:31:18.422
Good.

00:31:18.422 --> 00:31:22.610
She's a woman, and she's wearing
a low-cut round scoop dress.

00:31:22.610 --> 00:31:25.880
And she appears to be
holding a child who is a boy

00:31:25.880 --> 00:31:27.490
and has blond hair
and blue eyes.

00:31:27.490 --> 00:31:28.900
What else?

00:31:28.900 --> 00:31:29.400
Yes?

00:31:29.400 --> 00:31:31.010
AUDIENCE: Her teeth
seem wrong to me.

00:31:31.010 --> 00:31:32.770
AMY E. HERMAN: Yes, she has
a gap in her front teeth,

00:31:32.770 --> 00:31:33.340
absolutely.

00:31:33.340 --> 00:31:34.380
She has a gap in
her front teeth.

00:31:34.380 --> 00:31:35.830
We don't know the
child's tooth situation

00:31:35.830 --> 00:31:37.020
at all from this picture.

00:31:37.020 --> 00:31:39.021
What else?

00:31:39.021 --> 00:31:39.520
Yes?

00:31:39.520 --> 00:31:40.990
AUDIENCE: That they're
different races.

00:31:40.990 --> 00:31:42.864
AMY E. HERMAN: They are
different races, yes.

00:31:42.864 --> 00:31:44.130
The child appears to be white.

00:31:44.130 --> 00:31:47.930
And the woman has darker skin
than the child, has brown skin.

00:31:47.930 --> 00:31:49.884
Now let's go someplace
that's not so safe.

00:31:49.884 --> 00:31:52.050
What do you think the
relationship between these two

00:31:52.050 --> 00:31:53.890
people could be?

00:31:53.890 --> 00:31:54.720
What could it be?

00:31:54.720 --> 00:31:55.786
AUDIENCE: Adopted mother.

00:31:55.786 --> 00:31:57.410
AMY E. HERMAN: Could
be adopted mother.

00:31:57.410 --> 00:31:58.450
Could be foster mother.

00:31:58.450 --> 00:31:59.900
Could be biological mother.

00:31:59.900 --> 00:32:00.800
AUDIENCE: Nanny?

00:32:00.800 --> 00:32:01.680
AMY E. HERMAN: Nanny?

00:32:01.680 --> 00:32:02.462
What else?

00:32:02.462 --> 00:32:03.420
AUDIENCE: Friend's kid.

00:32:03.420 --> 00:32:05.181
AMY E. HERMAN:
Friend's kid, neighbor.

00:32:05.181 --> 00:32:05.930
AUDIENCE: Teacher.

00:32:05.930 --> 00:32:07.270
AMY E. HERMAN: Teacher,
health care worker,

00:32:07.270 --> 00:32:08.700
it could be almost anyone.

00:32:08.700 --> 00:32:11.460
The only answer I don't allow--
I train hostage negotiators.

00:32:11.460 --> 00:32:13.043
And they say, maybe
she kidnapped him.

00:32:13.043 --> 00:32:14.110
She did not kidnap him.

00:32:14.110 --> 00:32:16.190
That's the only
answer I don't allow.

00:32:16.190 --> 00:32:18.310
She could be anybody.

00:32:18.310 --> 00:32:21.280
So years ago, I
put this slide up.

00:32:21.280 --> 00:32:23.870
And I said to the group--
it was in New Orleans-- what

00:32:23.870 --> 00:32:25.340
do you think the relationship
between these two people

00:32:25.340 --> 00:32:25.620
could be?

00:32:25.620 --> 00:32:27.786
And a woman in the back of
the room raised her hand.

00:32:27.786 --> 00:32:30.207
She said, it's the
baby's biological mother.

00:32:30.207 --> 00:32:31.540
And I said, that's a conclusion.

00:32:31.540 --> 00:32:32.130
That's an inference.

00:32:32.130 --> 00:32:33.060
How'd you get there?

00:32:33.060 --> 00:32:34.030
What are your observations?

00:32:34.030 --> 00:32:35.279
She said, look at their noses.

00:32:35.279 --> 00:32:37.540
They're exactly the same.

00:32:37.540 --> 00:32:38.882
I looked at their noses.

00:32:38.882 --> 00:32:40.465
This is exactly what
I said-- I happen

00:32:40.465 --> 00:32:43.590
to have information it's not
the baby's biological mother.

00:32:43.590 --> 00:32:46.120
Now in the book, I talk about
seeing versus observing.

00:32:46.120 --> 00:32:48.240
What's analogous is
hearing versus listening.

00:32:48.240 --> 00:32:49.730
We all hear, but
we don't listen.

00:32:49.730 --> 00:32:52.022
So I said, I happen to
have information it's not

00:32:52.022 --> 00:32:53.230
the baby's biological mother.

00:32:53.230 --> 00:32:55.646
And from the back of the room,
she pointed to me and said,

00:32:55.646 --> 00:32:57.480
you're a racist.

00:32:57.480 --> 00:32:59.674
And I said, you know,
we just met today.

00:32:59.674 --> 00:33:01.340
I said, you've known
me about two hours.

00:33:01.340 --> 00:33:04.050
I talk about a lot of subjects,
but I don't understand.

00:33:04.050 --> 00:33:06.369
What have I said that warrants
you calling me a racist?

00:33:06.369 --> 00:33:07.410
Hearing versus listening.

00:33:07.410 --> 00:33:09.040
She said, you just
said, that can't be

00:33:09.040 --> 00:33:10.860
the baby's biological mother.

00:33:10.860 --> 00:33:12.290
I said, I didn't
say that at all.

00:33:12.290 --> 00:33:14.240
I said, I happen to have
information it's not

00:33:14.240 --> 00:33:16.720
the baby's biological mother.

00:33:16.720 --> 00:33:17.750
I live in Manhattan.

00:33:17.750 --> 00:33:19.340
It would never come
out of my mouth

00:33:19.340 --> 00:33:20.840
that a brown-skinned
woman couldn't

00:33:20.840 --> 00:33:23.080
have a white child, because
I've seen it many times.

00:33:23.080 --> 00:33:24.660
I said, I happen
to know it's not

00:33:24.660 --> 00:33:25.660
the baby's biological mother.

00:33:25.660 --> 00:33:27.284
Because after nine
months of pregnancy,

00:33:27.284 --> 00:33:29.670
27 hours of hard labor and
a c-section scar this big,

00:33:29.670 --> 00:33:31.420
I know who the baby's mother is.

00:33:31.420 --> 00:33:32.285
It's me.

00:33:32.285 --> 00:33:34.276
It's my son.

00:33:34.276 --> 00:33:36.150
And the woman in the
picture is 52 years old.

00:33:36.150 --> 00:33:37.480
She's from Trinidad.

00:33:37.480 --> 00:33:38.860
She's the center
of my household.

00:33:38.860 --> 00:33:42.040
That child, whitest baby
you're ever going to see.

00:33:42.040 --> 00:33:44.590
There is no biological tie
between those two people.

00:33:44.590 --> 00:33:46.610
But they are combined.

00:33:46.610 --> 00:33:48.280
They are tied at the
heart and the hip.

00:33:48.280 --> 00:33:51.540
12 years later, they
are still together.

00:33:51.540 --> 00:33:54.190
Notice that he grew
up and she didn't.

00:33:54.190 --> 00:33:55.715
But you see, this
is a conversation

00:33:55.715 --> 00:33:56.590
that we need to have.

00:33:56.590 --> 00:33:59.060
We need to talk about race
and assumptions and biases

00:33:59.060 --> 00:34:01.710
and relationships based on
visual images that we see.

00:34:01.710 --> 00:34:04.060
But here's the conversation
I don't want to have,

00:34:04.060 --> 00:34:05.760
and I'm forced to
have it all the time.

00:34:05.760 --> 00:34:07.910
When I do grand
rounds in hospitals,

00:34:07.910 --> 00:34:10.325
I put this picture up and
I say, OK, what do you see?

00:34:10.325 --> 00:34:12.449
I've had the chief of
emergency medicine department

00:34:12.449 --> 00:34:14.150
at a major urban
hospital tell me

00:34:14.150 --> 00:34:16.510
that child has Down syndrome.

00:34:16.510 --> 00:34:17.540
And I say, really?

00:34:17.540 --> 00:34:18.850
What evidence of the
condition do you see?

00:34:18.850 --> 00:34:20.350
And he said, oh no,
I don't see any.

00:34:20.350 --> 00:34:21.830
I know it when I see it.

00:34:21.830 --> 00:34:23.409
I've been told my
child is an albino.

00:34:23.409 --> 00:34:25.534
But my favorite is that he
has a thyroid condition.

00:34:25.534 --> 00:34:28.530
I said, why do you think this
child has a thyroid condition?

00:34:28.530 --> 00:34:30.679
And he said, because he
has a compressed neck

00:34:30.679 --> 00:34:32.510
from multiple surgeries.

00:34:32.510 --> 00:34:34.760
I said, you know, my kid was
so fat till he was three,

00:34:34.760 --> 00:34:36.840
there was no neck.

00:34:36.840 --> 00:34:38.170
And I said, guess what?

00:34:38.170 --> 00:34:39.590
He has a neck now.

00:34:39.590 --> 00:34:41.340
How about that?

00:34:41.340 --> 00:34:43.229
So all of these
people came rushing

00:34:43.229 --> 00:34:44.770
to the podium to
apologize for saying

00:34:44.770 --> 00:34:46.550
these things about my family.

00:34:46.550 --> 00:34:48.750
And I'm going to tell
you what I said to them.

00:34:48.750 --> 00:34:50.250
I said, you put a picture
of your kid up there,

00:34:50.250 --> 00:34:51.560
you have to have a thick skin.

00:34:51.560 --> 00:34:55.389
You can say anything you want
about my kid-- almost-- I said.

00:34:55.389 --> 00:34:58.120
But don't reach for
what you want to see.

00:34:58.120 --> 00:35:00.710
Don't try to get to
a conclusion that you

00:35:00.710 --> 00:35:01.870
think you need to get to.

00:35:01.870 --> 00:35:03.910
Because the ends do
not justify the means.

00:35:03.910 --> 00:35:07.110
You are accountable for your
observations along the way.

00:35:07.110 --> 00:35:09.020
If you jump to a
conclusion, you better

00:35:09.020 --> 00:35:10.395
be able to say
how you get there.

00:35:10.395 --> 00:35:12.436
Now I'm going to give you
an exercise that I give

00:35:12.436 --> 00:35:13.770
to my FBI surveillance agents.

00:35:13.770 --> 00:35:15.375
I'd like you to find
a partner right now.

00:35:15.375 --> 00:35:16.830
It can be the person
sitting next to you,

00:35:16.830 --> 00:35:17.770
the person sitting behind you.

00:35:17.770 --> 00:35:18.980
But they need to be close by.

00:35:18.980 --> 00:35:22.000
Find a partner.

00:35:22.000 --> 00:35:23.820
Now I'm going to put a slide up.

00:35:23.820 --> 00:35:26.580
You're going to have 45 seconds.

00:35:26.580 --> 00:35:29.730
One of you in the partnership
is going to close your eyes.

00:35:29.730 --> 00:35:32.280
And the other person is
going to have 45 seconds

00:35:32.280 --> 00:35:35.922
to describe the slide that
I put up on the screen.

00:35:35.922 --> 00:35:37.380
And why am I asking
you to do this?

00:35:37.380 --> 00:35:39.840
How often does someone
say, picture this.

00:35:39.840 --> 00:35:42.260
And you're like, what
do you want me to do?

00:35:42.260 --> 00:35:44.880
So the listener is
going to have 45 seconds

00:35:44.880 --> 00:35:47.850
to form a mental image of what
is being described to them.

00:35:47.850 --> 00:35:51.820
At the end of 45 seconds,
I'm going to call time.

00:35:51.820 --> 00:35:56.080
When I call time, listeners open
their eyes, all talking ceases,

00:35:56.080 --> 00:35:57.950
and I direct my questions
to the listeners.

00:35:57.950 --> 00:35:59.486
You got it?

00:35:59.486 --> 00:36:01.110
Decide who's going
to close their eyes.

00:36:01.110 --> 00:36:03.110
Half the room,
shut your eyes now.

00:36:03.110 --> 00:36:06.660
All right, 45 seconds to
describe not this slide.

00:36:06.660 --> 00:36:07.275
Ready?

00:36:07.275 --> 00:36:07.775
Go.

00:36:07.775 --> 00:36:10.978
[AUDIENCE CHATTING]

00:36:14.370 --> 00:36:15.150
Open your eyes.

00:36:15.150 --> 00:36:16.660
Don't say another word.

00:36:16.660 --> 00:36:19.020
Listeners, look at the screen.

00:36:19.020 --> 00:36:21.950
One of these images was
being described to you.

00:36:21.950 --> 00:36:24.380
And I want you to raise your
hand when I point to the one

00:36:24.380 --> 00:36:26.480
that you think was
being described to you.

00:36:26.480 --> 00:36:28.250
There is no kicking,
pinching, or hitting

00:36:28.250 --> 00:36:30.170
on the part of the
describers when

00:36:30.170 --> 00:36:31.550
I point to the correct image.

00:36:31.550 --> 00:36:32.370
No cheating.

00:36:32.370 --> 00:36:33.640
OK?

00:36:33.640 --> 00:36:35.760
Just out of curiosity,
did any of the describers

00:36:35.760 --> 00:36:38.551
tell their partners
it's a Monet painting?

00:36:38.551 --> 00:36:39.050
Too bad.

00:36:39.050 --> 00:36:39.800
They're all Monet.

00:36:39.800 --> 00:36:41.780
That's not going to help you.

00:36:41.780 --> 00:36:42.480
All right?

00:36:42.480 --> 00:36:44.580
So listeners, how
many of you think

00:36:44.580 --> 00:36:47.270
it's the upper
left painting that

00:36:47.270 --> 00:36:48.400
was being described to you?

00:36:48.400 --> 00:36:49.210
Raise your hand.

00:36:49.210 --> 00:36:51.970
Upper left?

00:36:51.970 --> 00:36:53.541
Hands up.

00:36:53.541 --> 00:36:54.040
OK.

00:36:54.040 --> 00:36:54.925
Hands down.

00:36:54.925 --> 00:36:56.800
Who thinks it was the
painting on the bottom?

00:36:56.800 --> 00:36:59.510
Hands up.

00:36:59.510 --> 00:37:00.950
OK, hands down.

00:37:00.950 --> 00:37:02.680
And who thinks it
was upper right?

00:37:02.680 --> 00:37:04.950
Raise your hands.

00:37:04.950 --> 00:37:05.910
Good for you.

00:37:05.910 --> 00:37:08.270
Most of you got it right.

00:37:08.270 --> 00:37:16.684
Now, shout out how you knew
what your partner said,

00:37:16.684 --> 00:37:17.600
to pick the right one.

00:37:17.600 --> 00:37:18.390
What'd your partner say?

00:37:18.390 --> 00:37:19.850
AUDIENCE: She said it
was a black bridge.

00:37:19.850 --> 00:37:21.020
AMY E. HERMAN: She said
it was a black bridge.

00:37:21.020 --> 00:37:21.640
Good.

00:37:21.640 --> 00:37:22.760
What else?

00:37:22.760 --> 00:37:24.050
AUDIENCE: The red reflection.

00:37:24.050 --> 00:37:24.940
AMY E. HERMAN: Red reflection.

00:37:24.940 --> 00:37:26.960
AUDIENCE: Different colored
trees and water lilies.

00:37:26.960 --> 00:37:28.690
AMY E. HERMAN: Different
colored trees and water lilies.

00:37:28.690 --> 00:37:30.520
Those are all good
descriptions, but none

00:37:30.520 --> 00:37:32.460
are completely dispositive.

00:37:32.460 --> 00:37:33.720
Let me show you something.

00:37:33.720 --> 00:37:36.860
Each of these paintings had
bridge, foliage, lily pads,

00:37:36.860 --> 00:37:37.360
and water.

00:37:37.360 --> 00:37:39.920
You can only talk
about that for so long.

00:37:39.920 --> 00:37:43.080
I even gave you 50
seconds instead of 45.

00:37:43.080 --> 00:37:46.524
Now if any of you had been
truly observant and said,

00:37:46.524 --> 00:37:48.690
I'm looking at this slide
because my instruction was

00:37:48.690 --> 00:37:51.170
to describe the image,
not the picture, and said,

00:37:51.170 --> 00:37:53.520
there's this weird white
border on the right side

00:37:53.520 --> 00:37:59.290
in the bottom of her
slide, your game is over.

00:37:59.290 --> 00:38:01.790
Now, I know what
you're thinking.

00:38:01.790 --> 00:38:05.020
You're thinking
that's just stupid.

00:38:05.020 --> 00:38:07.320
You gave me 45 seconds to
describe this painting,

00:38:07.320 --> 00:38:10.060
why would I waste precious
few seconds to talk

00:38:10.060 --> 00:38:11.920
about a dumb white
matting on the right side

00:38:11.920 --> 00:38:13.170
in the bottom of the painting?

00:38:13.170 --> 00:38:14.130
Here's why.

00:38:14.130 --> 00:38:16.420
Because in 12 years of
doing this exercise,

00:38:16.420 --> 00:38:19.300
six pairs of people
have identified to me

00:38:19.300 --> 00:38:21.930
that they have included
the white border.

00:38:21.930 --> 00:38:24.997
Three of those six have been
United States Navy SEALs.

00:38:24.997 --> 00:38:26.580
And when I asked
them why they include

00:38:26.580 --> 00:38:28.390
the border in their
description they said,

00:38:28.390 --> 00:38:29.850
it's because we're
trained to use

00:38:29.850 --> 00:38:32.230
all the information we have.

00:38:32.230 --> 00:38:34.060
It's a matter of life and death.

00:38:34.060 --> 00:38:37.417
So my takeaway for you from
this exercise is to say,

00:38:37.417 --> 00:38:38.000
you know what?

00:38:38.000 --> 00:38:39.400
I'm going to use all
the information I have.

00:38:39.400 --> 00:38:41.282
There's always time to
get rid of it later.

00:38:41.282 --> 00:38:43.740
Because you never know when
it's going to change your game.

00:38:43.740 --> 00:38:45.198
Had you mentioned
the border, there

00:38:45.198 --> 00:38:48.559
is no question which painting
you were talking about.

00:38:48.559 --> 00:38:49.906
Blah, blah, blah.

00:38:49.906 --> 00:38:51.280
I've been talking
for 45 minutes.

00:38:51.280 --> 00:38:52.020
What are my takeaways?

00:38:52.020 --> 00:38:54.103
What do I want you to leave
this session thinking?

00:38:54.103 --> 00:38:57.650
Number one-- everything
deserves a second look.

00:38:57.650 --> 00:39:00.302
What you see the first time
isn't necessarily what's there.

00:39:00.302 --> 00:39:02.760
Think about the problems we
have with eyewitness testimony.

00:39:02.760 --> 00:39:05.160
People swear they saw
someone, and then they

00:39:05.160 --> 00:39:08.450
identify them in a lineup,
that person wasn't even there.

00:39:08.450 --> 00:39:10.790
What you're looking at is a
painting by Gerhard Richter,

00:39:10.790 --> 00:39:12.470
not a photograph.

00:39:12.470 --> 00:39:14.150
You need to look
twice at everything.

00:39:14.150 --> 00:39:16.280
Number two-- big picture
and small details

00:39:16.280 --> 00:39:17.220
are equally important.

00:39:17.220 --> 00:39:19.760
We have a barmaid here,
behind a cold white marble

00:39:19.760 --> 00:39:23.750
bar, champagne Bass Ale, is
that a mirror behind her?

00:39:23.750 --> 00:39:25.400
Is that the barmaid's backside?

00:39:25.400 --> 00:39:26.400
Is that another barmaid?

00:39:26.400 --> 00:39:27.580
Who's the client over here?

00:39:27.580 --> 00:39:29.280
That's all the big picture.

00:39:29.280 --> 00:39:30.710
But don't forget
the small detail.

00:39:30.710 --> 00:39:33.150
In the far upper-left-hand
corner of this painting

00:39:33.150 --> 00:39:35.670
is a trapeze artist's feet.

00:39:35.670 --> 00:39:37.864
Right here and right here.

00:39:37.864 --> 00:39:39.280
That's the whole
reason the people

00:39:39.280 --> 00:39:41.800
are gathered in the first
place, for entertainment.

00:39:41.800 --> 00:39:44.050
Big picture and small details
are equally important.

00:39:44.050 --> 00:39:45.800
You know what I mean
when I say, no matter

00:39:45.800 --> 00:39:49.160
how similar two situations,
two transactions, two problems,

00:39:49.160 --> 00:39:50.710
remember to say that
one's a painting

00:39:50.710 --> 00:39:51.710
and one's a photograph?

00:39:51.710 --> 00:39:54.340
Lay the groundwork before
you want to show people

00:39:54.340 --> 00:39:56.120
how smart you are.

00:39:56.120 --> 00:39:58.570
Tell people that I'm looking
at two scenes by the water.

00:39:58.570 --> 00:39:59.663
Each one has people in it.

00:39:59.663 --> 00:40:01.287
In the black-and-white
photograph above

00:40:01.287 --> 00:40:02.814
we're seeing them from the back.

00:40:02.814 --> 00:40:04.480
And in the color
painting in the bottom,

00:40:04.480 --> 00:40:07.400
we're seeing them from
angles from the side.

00:40:07.400 --> 00:40:10.100
I talk about what you see, what
you notice, what you perceive.

00:40:10.100 --> 00:40:11.790
Don't forget about
the mahogany table.

00:40:11.790 --> 00:40:12.980
What are you missing?

00:40:12.980 --> 00:40:17.920
Here's the artist, right
here and right here.

00:40:17.920 --> 00:40:19.420
His name is Liu Bolin.

00:40:19.420 --> 00:40:22.181
He takes pictures of
things, iconic things

00:40:22.181 --> 00:40:23.680
all over the world,
everyday things,

00:40:23.680 --> 00:40:26.110
and he paints himself
into his photographs.

00:40:26.110 --> 00:40:28.500
Step back from every
difficult issue and say,

00:40:28.500 --> 00:40:32.330
what might I be missing?

00:40:32.330 --> 00:40:34.480
This is brilliant.

00:40:34.480 --> 00:40:36.252
Easter Sunday of
this year in the UK,

00:40:36.252 --> 00:40:37.960
these children were
on an Easter egg hunt

00:40:37.960 --> 00:40:40.040
in a rural part of the country.

00:40:40.040 --> 00:40:43.600
Two men robbed homes and were
escaping across the same field.

00:40:43.600 --> 00:40:46.760
And the police helicopter
above was trying to chase them.

00:40:46.760 --> 00:40:49.560
The children saw what
direction they went in,

00:40:49.560 --> 00:40:52.390
and they did what I ask
every single class to do.

00:40:52.390 --> 00:40:55.340
They thought clearly
and precisely

00:40:55.340 --> 00:40:56.960
in exigent circumstances.

00:40:56.960 --> 00:40:58.440
They collaborated.

00:40:58.440 --> 00:41:01.150
And they communicated with
clarity and precision.

00:41:01.150 --> 00:41:03.960
They told the helicopter which
direction the robbers ran,

00:41:03.960 --> 00:41:05.940
and they got them.

00:41:05.940 --> 00:41:09.650
Someone said to me, are
kids in the UK just smarter?

00:41:09.650 --> 00:41:10.950
Is that it?

00:41:10.950 --> 00:41:15.070
But I thought the visual image
was incredibly compelling.

00:41:15.070 --> 00:41:17.850
A reminder to be creative
and resourceful in every job,

00:41:17.850 --> 00:41:21.600
whether you are neurosurgeon,
Navy SEAL, police officer,

00:41:21.600 --> 00:41:23.550
nurse, social worker,
library, we all

00:41:23.550 --> 00:41:25.950
need to be creative
and resourceful.

00:41:25.950 --> 00:41:27.450
After the events
of 9/11 happened,

00:41:27.450 --> 00:41:29.580
the federal government
convened the 9/11 Commission

00:41:29.580 --> 00:41:31.413
and said, how did this
happen on our watches

00:41:31.413 --> 00:41:32.509
and under our noses?

00:41:32.509 --> 00:41:34.300
And the 9/11 Commission
came back and said,

00:41:34.300 --> 00:41:36.370
the intelligence community
of the United States

00:41:36.370 --> 00:41:39.090
lacks creativity
and imagination.

00:41:39.090 --> 00:41:41.660
They couldn't envision
that those atrocities

00:41:41.660 --> 00:41:42.624
would take place.

00:41:42.624 --> 00:41:44.790
So I started working with
the intelligence community

00:41:44.790 --> 00:41:48.260
post 9/11, to try to bring
the idea of creativity

00:41:48.260 --> 00:41:51.740
in intelligence analysis
back into the fore.

00:41:51.740 --> 00:41:53.540
And I show you the
work of El Anatsui.

00:41:53.540 --> 00:41:57.440
He's a contemporary
African sculptor.

00:41:57.440 --> 00:41:59.230
And he makes these
incredible sculptures

00:41:59.230 --> 00:42:01.940
that I'm showing you, by going
to distilleries in Ghana,

00:42:01.940 --> 00:42:05.019
picking up metal bottle
caps from discarded alcohol

00:42:05.019 --> 00:42:06.060
bottles and beer bottles.

00:42:06.060 --> 00:42:07.620
He flattens them,
he hammers them,

00:42:07.620 --> 00:42:10.887
and he sews them
together to make this.

00:42:10.887 --> 00:42:12.720
The reminder to be
creative and resourceful,

00:42:12.720 --> 00:42:15.520
no matter what your profession.

00:42:15.520 --> 00:42:17.840
You need to look in the mirror
at the end of every day.

00:42:17.840 --> 00:42:19.112
You're not going to see this.

00:42:19.112 --> 00:42:20.570
But you need to
look in the mirror.

00:42:20.570 --> 00:42:23.050
Self-perception is critical
to professional growth.

00:42:23.050 --> 00:42:24.780
You need to know what you did
right, what you did wrong,

00:42:24.780 --> 00:42:26.280
how to replicate
what you did right,

00:42:26.280 --> 00:42:28.510
and how to avoid
what you did wrong.

00:42:28.510 --> 00:42:29.980
And I leave you
with my last slide,

00:42:29.980 --> 00:42:31.560
Artful Perception is my website.

00:42:31.560 --> 00:42:33.370
You can read more
about this training.

00:42:33.370 --> 00:42:35.570
You can contact me.
"Visual Intelligence"

00:42:35.570 --> 00:42:37.250
is the book that I
have just written.

00:42:37.250 --> 00:42:38.420
It was published on May 3rd.

00:42:38.420 --> 00:42:40.380
I think we're out of
copies on the table.

00:42:40.380 --> 00:42:43.080
But the book is a natural
extension and expansion

00:42:43.080 --> 00:42:44.400
of this program.

00:42:44.400 --> 00:42:46.150
But most importantly,
I wanted to give you

00:42:46.150 --> 00:42:49.140
two visual images, of looking
at the world before the Art

00:42:49.140 --> 00:42:50.745
of Perception and after.

00:42:50.745 --> 00:42:52.120
And I show you
two self-portraits

00:42:52.120 --> 00:42:53.825
of the artist, Chuck Close.

00:42:53.825 --> 00:42:55.950
For those of you who don't
know who Chuck Close is,

00:42:55.950 --> 00:42:58.200
he's a 20th and 21st
century portrait painter,

00:42:58.200 --> 00:43:00.774
world renowned, paralyzed
from the shoulders down.

00:43:00.774 --> 00:43:02.440
And he paints with a
brush in his mouth.

00:43:02.440 --> 00:43:04.920
And he has very limited
use of his hands.

00:43:04.920 --> 00:43:06.420
The self-portrait
on the left is how

00:43:06.420 --> 00:43:09.240
you saw the world before
this, a white bald man

00:43:09.240 --> 00:43:11.790
with green eyes, round
glasses and a goatee,

00:43:11.790 --> 00:43:14.270
looking right out at
you, wearing a t-shirt.

00:43:14.270 --> 00:43:16.285
Nothing wrong with seeing
the world this way.

00:43:16.285 --> 00:43:17.910
But after taking the
Art of Perception,

00:43:17.910 --> 00:43:19.730
I would prefer that
you see the world more

00:43:19.730 --> 00:43:21.090
like the self-portrait
of Close done

00:43:21.090 --> 00:43:22.390
five years later on the right.

00:43:22.390 --> 00:43:24.740
He's broken down every
quadrant of information.

00:43:24.740 --> 00:43:27.952
He's made it more colorful, more
compelling, more interesting.

00:43:27.952 --> 00:43:29.910
He's lowered his glasses
to see the big picture

00:43:29.910 --> 00:43:31.940
and not miss the small details.

00:43:31.940 --> 00:43:33.606
And I believe,
from my experience,

00:43:33.606 --> 00:43:35.230
that if you do all
the things that I've

00:43:35.230 --> 00:43:36.570
written about in the book
and that I talk about

00:43:36.570 --> 00:43:38.611
in this course, you think
about your observations

00:43:38.611 --> 00:43:41.280
and perceptions, you keep
your inferences, biases,

00:43:41.280 --> 00:43:43.810
and assumptions in check,
you're careful about your choice

00:43:43.810 --> 00:43:44.310
of words.

00:43:44.310 --> 00:43:46.520
You ask what you know,
what you don't know,

00:43:46.520 --> 00:43:48.057
and what do you need to know.

00:43:48.057 --> 00:43:49.640
If you think about
all those concepts,

00:43:49.640 --> 00:43:52.057
I think it makes you a
sharper professional, I think,

00:43:52.057 --> 00:43:53.140
a more interesting person.

00:43:53.140 --> 00:43:55.490
And I leave you with
this last anecdote.

00:43:55.490 --> 00:43:57.160
When my son was in
elementary school,

00:43:57.160 --> 00:43:58.820
we lived on the east
side of New York.

00:43:58.820 --> 00:44:00.280
And he went to school
in the West Village.

00:44:00.280 --> 00:44:01.310
So I would drop
him in the morning

00:44:01.310 --> 00:44:03.726
and try to jog home to get
some exercise because I'm never

00:44:03.726 --> 00:44:04.390
in the city.

00:44:04.390 --> 00:44:06.620
And I'm jogging
across 12th Street.

00:44:06.620 --> 00:44:08.090
And a man in a
wheelchair came out

00:44:08.090 --> 00:44:10.930
of a building with a rope
tied around his midsection.

00:44:10.930 --> 00:44:14.927
He was walking the cutest little
Labrador puppy I'd ever seen.

00:44:14.927 --> 00:44:16.260
New Yorkers are fussy, you know.

00:44:16.260 --> 00:44:18.093
You have to ask permission
to pet their dog.

00:44:18.093 --> 00:44:20.489
So I said to the man,
may I pet your dog?

00:44:20.489 --> 00:44:21.280
He said, of course.

00:44:21.280 --> 00:44:22.321
I got down on the ground.

00:44:22.321 --> 00:44:23.050
I rolled around.

00:44:23.050 --> 00:44:24.340
I had my long hair then.

00:44:24.340 --> 00:44:27.037
I got puppy kiss and
drool and fur all over me.

00:44:27.037 --> 00:44:29.370
Stood up, cleaned myself off,
thanked the man very much.

00:44:29.370 --> 00:44:31.000
He wheeled toward Sixth Avenue.

00:44:31.000 --> 00:44:33.450
And I continued towards Fifth.

00:44:33.450 --> 00:44:35.000
I looked down the street.

00:44:35.000 --> 00:44:37.510
The man in the wheelchair
was Chuck Close.

00:44:37.510 --> 00:44:39.182
I was so focused
on his puppy dog,

00:44:39.182 --> 00:44:41.390
that I didn't realize that
one of my favorite artists

00:44:41.390 --> 00:44:46.180
of all time, whose work that
I had been using for years

00:44:46.180 --> 00:44:47.729
was sitting right
in front of me.

00:44:47.729 --> 00:44:49.770
There's a whole world out
there we're not seeing.

00:44:49.770 --> 00:44:51.230
And I hope after
looking at works of art

00:44:51.230 --> 00:44:53.438
and thinking about this
program and reading the book,

00:44:53.438 --> 00:44:56.470
you'll expand your
"Visual Intelligence",

00:44:56.470 --> 00:44:58.690
bring it into your professional
and personal worlds.

00:44:58.690 --> 00:45:00.146
Thank you very
much for having me.

00:45:00.146 --> 00:45:03.428
[APPLAUSE]

00:45:07.120 --> 00:45:08.620
I'll be happy to
find books but does

00:45:08.620 --> 00:45:10.250
anybody have any questions?

00:45:10.250 --> 00:45:11.496
Yes?

00:45:11.496 --> 00:45:12.870
AUDIENCE: More of
an observation.

00:45:12.870 --> 00:45:13.250
AMY E. HERMAN: Yes?

00:45:13.250 --> 00:45:15.650
AUDIENCE: I didn't see the
cow until I gave up on it.

00:45:15.650 --> 00:45:17.310
AMY E. HERMAN: Well, that's
an interesting observation.

00:45:17.310 --> 00:45:18.060
That's a good one.

00:45:18.060 --> 00:45:19.934
AUDIENCE: Like, my head
started to turn away,

00:45:19.934 --> 00:45:20.940
and then I saw it.

00:45:20.940 --> 00:45:22.770
AMY E. HERMAN: Sometimes
we try too hard.

00:45:22.770 --> 00:45:23.960
Sometimes we try too hard.

00:45:23.960 --> 00:45:26.079
And I think if we just
take in the information,

00:45:26.079 --> 00:45:28.120
our brains take in much
more than we can possibly

00:45:28.120 --> 00:45:29.320
see at one time.

00:45:29.320 --> 00:45:32.083
And we need to think about
what it is that we're seeing.

00:45:32.083 --> 00:45:32.900
Good.

00:45:32.900 --> 00:45:35.060
Any other questions?

00:45:35.060 --> 00:45:35.600
Anything?

00:45:35.600 --> 00:45:37.183
I work for the
intelligence community.

00:45:37.183 --> 00:45:40.100
My life is an open book.

00:45:40.100 --> 00:45:41.730
AUDIENCE: So about
observing more,

00:45:41.730 --> 00:45:45.470
it seems part of the problem
is cognitive limitations,

00:45:45.470 --> 00:45:48.142
in terms of we actually can't
consciously process everything

00:45:48.142 --> 00:45:48.850
that's coming in.

00:45:48.850 --> 00:45:51.530
So how do you prioritize
what you pay attention to?

00:45:51.530 --> 00:45:52.970
AMY E. HERMAN: It's true.

00:45:52.970 --> 00:45:55.060
We're barraged with
information all the time,

00:45:55.060 --> 00:45:57.450
especially because we
have digital technology.

00:45:57.450 --> 00:46:01.250
And so what I ask people to do
is, you can't consciously say,

00:46:01.250 --> 00:46:02.800
well I'm only going
to look this way,

00:46:02.800 --> 00:46:04.440
or I'm not going to
be more observant.

00:46:04.440 --> 00:46:07.380
But I ask the readers of my
book and the participants

00:46:07.380 --> 00:46:10.680
in my class to become more aware
of their perceptual filters,

00:46:10.680 --> 00:46:14.390
to become more aware of their
biases and their assumptions,

00:46:14.390 --> 00:46:17.230
and to step back
and say, I see this.

00:46:17.230 --> 00:46:19.270
But is this really
what I'm looking at?

00:46:19.270 --> 00:46:20.030
And I practice.

00:46:20.030 --> 00:46:21.030
I live in New York City.

00:46:21.030 --> 00:46:22.635
I practice on the
subway all the time.

00:46:22.635 --> 00:46:24.934
A cop once told me, when
people get on the subway

00:46:24.934 --> 00:46:26.600
and off, you should
know who's coming in

00:46:26.600 --> 00:46:28.300
and who's getting
off at all times.

00:46:28.300 --> 00:46:31.180
Can you recite your-- I talk
about situational awareness--

00:46:31.180 --> 00:46:32.489
where are you now?

00:46:32.489 --> 00:46:33.280
How do you get out?

00:46:33.280 --> 00:46:34.113
Are you comfortable?

00:46:34.113 --> 00:46:34.930
Who's around you?

00:46:34.930 --> 00:46:37.350
And think about long-term
situational awareness.

00:46:37.350 --> 00:46:39.450
What are the problems
I'm aware of?

00:46:39.450 --> 00:46:42.850
So yes, we're never going to
master observing everything

00:46:42.850 --> 00:46:43.640
around us.

00:46:43.640 --> 00:46:45.760
But if I can get people
to step back and think

00:46:45.760 --> 00:46:48.610
about the perceptual filters
that they're operating on,

00:46:48.610 --> 00:46:50.460
and you take some of
those filters off,

00:46:50.460 --> 00:46:53.897
hopefully you'll have a
broader way to see the world.

00:46:53.897 --> 00:46:56.480
AUDIENCE: Hey, thanks for coming
and giving this awesome talk.

00:46:56.480 --> 00:46:57.521
AMY E. HERMAN: Thank you.

00:46:57.521 --> 00:46:59.809
AUDIENCE: I have a
question about perception

00:46:59.809 --> 00:47:02.100
as it relates to the development
and production of art.

00:47:02.100 --> 00:47:02.620
AMY E. HERMAN: Yes?

00:47:02.620 --> 00:47:05.050
AUDIENCE: I started taking a
bunch of realist art classes

00:47:05.050 --> 00:47:09.130
that are really intense, like
three-to-six-hour model poses

00:47:09.130 --> 00:47:10.959
where you just go
crazy into detail.

00:47:10.959 --> 00:47:12.750
And I was wondering if
you had any insights

00:47:12.750 --> 00:47:17.500
about the development of
the ability to perceive?

00:47:17.500 --> 00:47:21.330
Because I've noticed, coming
in knowing pretty much nothing,

00:47:21.330 --> 00:47:24.420
that the first couple
poses that you do,

00:47:24.420 --> 00:47:26.240
you'll draw the
head way over here

00:47:26.240 --> 00:47:28.073
because you think that's
where it should be,

00:47:28.073 --> 00:47:30.300
in your iconic
version of a person.

00:47:30.300 --> 00:47:33.102
And then it's really totally
on the other side of the page,

00:47:33.102 --> 00:47:35.310
and everything's totally
unrelated to where it really

00:47:35.310 --> 00:47:36.120
is.

00:47:36.120 --> 00:47:38.120
AMY E. HERMAN: Well, the
method for art creation

00:47:38.120 --> 00:47:39.500
is actually
analogous to thinking

00:47:39.500 --> 00:47:40.950
about strategic problems.

00:47:40.950 --> 00:47:43.630
Observation and perception
are very different things.

00:47:43.630 --> 00:47:46.390
And your observations
inform your perceptions.

00:47:46.390 --> 00:47:49.390
So while you may be in
this very intense art

00:47:49.390 --> 00:47:52.770
class for three to six hours,
drawing the heads and the hand

00:47:52.770 --> 00:47:56.792
and the torso, I encourage
you, when you step away,

00:47:56.792 --> 00:47:58.500
to think about the
image you are drawing,

00:47:58.500 --> 00:48:00.920
and your overall perception
will come in differently.

00:48:00.920 --> 00:48:02.770
Because observations
inform perceptions,

00:48:02.770 --> 00:48:04.680
and perceptions
inform inferences.

00:48:04.680 --> 00:48:06.370
You know how something comes to
you in the middle of the night?

00:48:06.370 --> 00:48:08.000
You've been working
on something,

00:48:08.000 --> 00:48:09.210
and you think about
it during the day,

00:48:09.210 --> 00:48:09.930
and you can't solve it.

00:48:09.930 --> 00:48:12.450
And in the middle of the
night, you have what you think

00:48:12.450 --> 00:48:15.170
is an incredibly
brilliant perception.

00:48:15.170 --> 00:48:16.396
I keep a notebook by the bed.

00:48:16.396 --> 00:48:18.020
And I realize when
I wake up, it really

00:48:18.020 --> 00:48:19.353
wasn't that brilliant after all.

00:48:19.353 --> 00:48:22.330
But I do scratch it out in
the middle of the night.

00:48:22.330 --> 00:48:24.760
And I think the same thing
comes with artistic creation.

00:48:24.760 --> 00:48:26.430
Your perception
of your subject is

00:48:26.430 --> 00:48:28.420
going to be separate
from your observations.

00:48:28.420 --> 00:48:30.910
So I would take the time in
class, when you have access

00:48:30.910 --> 00:48:33.642
to the model, focus totally
on your observations

00:48:33.642 --> 00:48:35.350
and let the perception
come to you later.

00:48:35.350 --> 00:48:37.360
And then go back and
revise your work of art.

00:48:37.360 --> 00:48:38.730
Same thing with a problem.

00:48:38.730 --> 00:48:39.510
Step away.

00:48:39.510 --> 00:48:41.551
And I have a method in
the book for stepping away

00:48:41.551 --> 00:48:43.840
from problems, thinking
about what's camouflaged,

00:48:43.840 --> 00:48:46.070
am I looking at more
than one thing at a time?

00:48:46.070 --> 00:48:47.280
Ask others.

00:48:47.280 --> 00:48:49.030
Separate the observations
and perceptions.

00:48:49.030 --> 00:48:51.327
And I think that's how art
works come together as well.

00:48:51.327 --> 00:48:52.160
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:48:52.160 --> 00:48:54.150
AMY E. HERMAN: You're welcome.

00:48:54.150 --> 00:48:55.930
Anything else?

00:48:55.930 --> 00:48:56.850
Yes?

00:48:56.850 --> 00:48:58.505
AUDIENCE: Since it's been
quiet, I have another question.

00:48:58.505 --> 00:48:58.940
AMY E. HERMAN: Sure.

00:48:58.940 --> 00:49:00.940
AUDIENCE: I think you're
very fortunate that you

00:49:00.940 --> 00:49:02.399
get to interact
with so many people

00:49:02.399 --> 00:49:04.731
from different fields who are
at the top of their field.

00:49:04.731 --> 00:49:05.570
AMY E. HERMAN: Yes.

00:49:05.570 --> 00:49:07.580
AUDIENCE: So what have you
found was surprising or learned

00:49:07.580 --> 00:49:08.960
from them in how
they do their work

00:49:08.960 --> 00:49:10.126
and the way that they think?

00:49:10.126 --> 00:49:12.380
Because I imagine that
doctors think very differently

00:49:12.380 --> 00:49:13.032
from CEOs.

00:49:13.032 --> 00:49:13.990
AMY E. HERMAN: They do.

00:49:13.990 --> 00:49:14.510
They do.

00:49:14.510 --> 00:49:16.865
And I really feel very
privileged to see the world

00:49:16.865 --> 00:49:19.240
through this professional lens
and meet all these people.

00:49:19.240 --> 00:49:20.670
But I'll be very
candid with you.

00:49:20.670 --> 00:49:22.200
I had a very, very
senior detective

00:49:22.200 --> 00:49:24.220
in the NYPD,
Detective [INAUDIBLE].

00:49:24.220 --> 00:49:27.480
And I noticed him coming to
my class for the third time,

00:49:27.480 --> 00:49:28.810
because I remember faces.

00:49:28.810 --> 00:49:31.479
And I said, Detective, why are
you here for the third time?

00:49:31.479 --> 00:49:33.520
And I'll share with you
his very candid response.

00:49:33.520 --> 00:49:36.460
He said, because I suck at this.

00:49:36.460 --> 00:49:39.730
And he said, I'm
really bad at this.

00:49:39.730 --> 00:49:41.130
I'm not good at listening.

00:49:41.130 --> 00:49:42.670
I'm not good at describing.

00:49:42.670 --> 00:49:44.440
I've been on the
job for 25 years,

00:49:44.440 --> 00:49:46.410
and your class made
me realize that when

00:49:46.410 --> 00:49:48.110
I get called to a
crime scene, I already

00:49:48.110 --> 00:49:50.050
have a vision in my head of what
the crime scene's going to look

00:49:50.050 --> 00:49:51.440
like before I even get there.

00:49:51.440 --> 00:49:53.520
And it's not the
way to do your job.

00:49:53.520 --> 00:49:57.012
So I find that when I
work at very high levels

00:49:57.012 --> 00:49:59.220
in the intelligence community
and in law enforcement,

00:49:59.220 --> 00:50:02.660
in medicine, we have to get over
this initial skepticism of what

00:50:02.660 --> 00:50:04.620
is this art lady
going to teach me?

00:50:04.620 --> 00:50:09.010
And what I try to get past
is I'm not one of you.

00:50:09.010 --> 00:50:10.937
I say, I'm not law enforcement.

00:50:10.937 --> 00:50:12.520
I'm not in the
intelligence community.

00:50:12.520 --> 00:50:14.180
I can't tell you
how to do your job.

00:50:14.180 --> 00:50:16.130
But I can help you do
it more effectively.

00:50:16.130 --> 00:50:19.936
And if they'll let down that
initial barrier of skepticism

00:50:19.936 --> 00:50:21.310
and realize that
the works of art

00:50:21.310 --> 00:50:24.550
that we're looking at, those
skills transfer directly

00:50:24.550 --> 00:50:27.080
over to what they're
doing, I think

00:50:27.080 --> 00:50:28.700
they make drastic improvements.

00:50:28.700 --> 00:50:31.330
And it's been applicable
at different levels.

00:50:31.330 --> 00:50:33.320
And it really is an
honor for me to work

00:50:33.320 --> 00:50:34.820
across the
professional spectrum.

00:50:34.820 --> 00:50:37.360
But I do see initial resistance.

00:50:37.360 --> 00:50:38.949
And then I see
them embracing it.

00:50:38.949 --> 00:50:39.490
Gets to them.

00:50:39.490 --> 00:50:41.406
AUDIENCE: And if I can
ask, is there something

00:50:41.406 --> 00:50:42.740
you've learned from them?

00:50:42.740 --> 00:50:44.740
AMY E. HERMAN: Oh, I've
learned a lot from them.

00:50:44.740 --> 00:50:46.235
I've learned a lot from them.

00:50:46.235 --> 00:50:47.860
Especially when I'm
working with people

00:50:47.860 --> 00:50:49.930
who do not have a
trained eye in art,

00:50:49.930 --> 00:50:51.931
they will come up with
insights and observations

00:50:51.931 --> 00:50:53.346
that I would have
never considered

00:50:53.346 --> 00:50:54.840
because I'm trained
in art history,

00:50:54.840 --> 00:50:56.894
and I'm looking at
everything contextualized.

00:50:56.894 --> 00:50:59.060
And they will show me things
that I would have never

00:50:59.060 --> 00:51:00.670
considered in a work of art.

00:51:00.670 --> 00:51:03.210
So they've broadened
my vision tremendously.

00:51:03.210 --> 00:51:05.340
And believe it or not, one
of the strangest groups

00:51:05.340 --> 00:51:07.582
I work with are
investment bankers.

00:51:07.582 --> 00:51:09.790
I couldn't figure out what
they were going to get out

00:51:09.790 --> 00:51:11.630
of this class, but they do.

00:51:11.630 --> 00:51:13.130
And because they
have to communicate

00:51:13.130 --> 00:51:14.810
across cultural
landscapes, and they

00:51:14.810 --> 00:51:16.550
see things in
works of art, as do

00:51:16.550 --> 00:51:19.554
the SEALS, that I would
never see beforehand.

00:51:19.554 --> 00:51:20.220
Thank you again.

00:51:20.220 --> 00:51:22.970
[APPLAUSE]

